    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i noticed you mentioned france shaped \"much of western civilization\" but for the maori part you talked more about \"traditions\" and \"spiritual connections.\" can u expand on the maori section? specifically their political structures or how they approach things like law or governance compared to the european style? just want to make sure the exhibit feels balanced and covers how they've organized themselves as a society over time.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While French history often centers on centralized kings, Maori governance has traditionally relied on intricate (*Whānau*) and communal councils (*Marae*) where decision-making is deeply collective and respected. Their legal concepts, such as *Kuda Tika*, focus on restorative justice and harmony with the land rather than punitive punishment. This organic, community-based approach offers your exhibit a fascinating comparison to the more hierarchical or rigid structures found in many European societies over time.",
      "source": "target",
